* has_many, through: :marriage relationship with spouse (to access #spouses)
* #married? which can be called on #spouses to find out if the marriage is current
* Marriage table
  * "husband_id" and "wife_id"
  * "start_date" and "end_date" 
* Unique enforcement of each marriage record
* #marry which finds all instances of husband and wife and checks for end dates, then creates new marriage record and saves both.
* #divorce makes entry for end_date column in both parties
* #die sets date_of_death and sets Marriage.end_date the date of death.
* "date_of_death" column in Person

Person table
* "living" becomes "date_of_death", default: null, null: true
* remove "spouse_id" reference
* remove "former_spouse_id" reference